result.execSummary:
The defendant Nichole L. Atikmen was found guilty of the following charge(s) in this case.

  • Battery [Modifiers: Domestic Abuse, Repeater], a class A misdemeanor, Wisconsin Statutes 940.19(1).

Charge(s) in this case were read in to this or other case(s). A "read in" charge is a charge that is dismissed as part of a plea agreement, however:

  • The defendant agrees to have the court consider the charge(s) when sentencing for another crime, under Wis. Stats. 973.20(1g)(b); and
  • The defendant cannot be prosecuted for these charge(s) in the future.

Notice to employers: It may be a violation of state law to discriminate against a job applicant because of an arrest or conviction record. Generally speaking, an employer may refuse to hire an applicant on the basis of a conviction only if the circumstances of the conviction substantially relate to the particular job. For more information, see Wisconsin Statute 111.335 and the Department of Workforce Development's publication, Arrest and Conviction Records under the Law.

records.addlTxt: ADA Melissa Inlow appears for the State.  Defendant appeared in person, in custody and with Attorney Ritland.  Defendant plead no contest to Count 1.  Count 2 dismissed, but read in for sentencing purposes.  Court recited the charges and possible penalties that the defendant plead to.  She understands.  Court reviewed the plea questionnaire, elements and constitutional rights with the defendant.  She understood.  Defense stipulated to a factual basis for the pleas.  Court found that the defendant entered her plea and waived her constitutional rights freely, voluntarily, and intelligently.  Court found that a factual basis exists for the plea.  Found guilty as plead to.  Joint recommendation for 4-6 months, consecutive to SEHR cases.  Concurrent to 15CM190.  May serve on EMP.  Defendant elected to exercise her right to allocution.  Court ordered:  4 months, consecutive to SEHR cases.  Concurrent to 15CM190.  May serve on EMP.  CC  payable @ $50/mo 2/1/16.    Failure to pay any part of the fine or court costs in full by the due date will result in 1 day jail for each $25 left unpaid.
